07320nam a22010575i 9781684482108DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20202020pau    fo  d z      eng d  a2019043878  a97816844821087 a10.36019/97816844821082doi  a(DE-B1597)567778  a(OCoLC)1181849913  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA00aBF717b.P5764 2020 4aBF717 7aLIT0000002bisacsh04a306.4/81  aGK 1229qDE-24/20sred2rvk00aPlay in the Age of Goethe :bTheories, Narratives, and Practices of Play around 1800 /ced. by Elliott Schreiber, Edgar Landgraf. 1aLewisburg, PA : bBucknell University Press, c[2020] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (340 p.) :b5 b&w images  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aNew Studies in the Age of Goethe00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tIntroduction: Play in the Age of Goethe and Today -- tPart I. Free Play -- tCHAPTER ONE. Beauty and Erotic Play: Anacreontic Poetry's Transformation of Aesthetic Philosophy -- tCHAPTER TWO. Free Play in German Idealism and Poststructuralism -- tPart II. Games of Chance -- tCHAPTER THREE. "Mit dem Spiele spielen": Lessing's Play for Tolerance -- tCHAPTER FOUR. Play with Memory and Its Topoi -- tPart III. Children's Play -- tCHAPTER FIVE. Narcissus at Play: Goethe, Piaget, and the Passage from Egocentric to Social Play -- tCHAPTER SIX. Playthings: Goethe's Favorite Toys -- tCHAPTER SEVEN. Kindergarten and the Pedagogy of Play in the German Educational Revolution -- tInterlude -- tCHAPTER EIGHT. Invective, Eulogy, Play: Jacobi's Sock 1799 -- tPart IV. The Play of Language -- tCHAPTER NINE. Between Speaking and Listening: Jean Paul's Wordplay -- tCHAPTER TEN. Authorship, Translation, Play: Schleiermacher's Metalangual Poetics -- tCHAPTER ELEVEN. Playing with Words in Early German Romanticism -- tAcknowledgments -- tBibliography -- tNotes on Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWe are inundated with game play today. Digital devices offer opportunities to play almost anywhere and anytime. No matter our age, gender, social, cultural, or educational background-we play. Play in the Age of Goethe: Theories, Narratives, and Practices of Play around 1800 is the first book-length work to explore how the modern discourse of play was first shaped during this pivotal period (approximately 1770-1830). The eleven chapters illuminate critical developments in the philosophy, pedagogy, psychology, politics, and poetics of play as evident in the work of major authors of the period including Lessing, Goethe, Kant, Schiller, Pestalozzi, Jacobi, Tieck, Jean Paul, Schleiermacher, and Fröbel. While drawing on more recent theories of play by thinkers such as Jean Piaget, Donald Winnicott, Jost Trier, Gregory Bateson, Jacques Derrida, Thomas Henricks, and Patrick Jagoda, the volume shows the debates around play in German letters of this period to be far richer and more complex than previously thought, as well as more relevant for our current engagement with play. Indeed, modern debates about what constitutes good rather than bad practices of play can be traced to these foundational discourses. Published by Bucknell University Press. Distributed worldwide by Rutgers University Press.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aPlayxPsychological aspectsxHistoryy18th century. 0aPlayxPsychological aspectsxHistoryy19th century. 0aPlayxSocial aspectsxHistoryy18th century. 0aPlayxSocial aspectsxHistoryy19th century. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / General.2bisacsh1 aFrey, Christiane, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFrey, Christiane.1 aHeidepriem, Samuel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeidepriem, Samuel.1 aLa